explanation: The condition line used `or` incorrectly: `if [s1, s2]==["#.",".#"] or[".#","#."]:` evaluates the second operand `['.#', '#.']` as a truthy list, so the whole condition is always true when the first comparison is false. I fixed it by comparing [s1, s2] to the second list as well: `or [s1, s2] == ['.#', '#.']` so both comparisons are boolean expressions.
fixed_code:
s1 = input()
s2 = input()

if [s1, s2] == ["#.", ".#"] or [s1, s2] == [".#", "#."]:
    print('No')
    exit()
else:
    print('Yes')
